-04"}
{"id":"1604.05734","submitter":"Ryan Martin","authors":"Ryan Martin and Stephen G. Walker","title":"Data-driven priors and their posterior concentration rates","comments":"31 pages","journal-ref":"Electronic Journal of Statistics, 2019, volume 13, number 2, pages\n  3049--3081","doi":"10.1214/19-EJS1600","report-no":null,"categories":"math.ST stat.TH","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In high-dimensional problems, choosing a prior distribution such that the\ncorresponding posterior has desirable practical and theoretical properties can\nbe challenging. This begs the question: can the data be used to help choose a\ngood prior? In this paper, we develop a general strategy for constructing a\ndata-driven or empirical prior and sufficient conditions for the corresponding\nposterior distribution to achieve a certain concentration rate. The idea is\nthat the prior should put sufficient mass on parameter values for which the\nlikelihood is large. An interesting byproduct of this data-driven centering is\nthat the asymptotic properties of the posterior are less sensitive to the prior\nshape which, in turn, allows users to work with priors of computationally\nconvenient forms while maintaining the desired rates. General results on both\nadaptive and non-adaptive rates based on empirical priors are presented, along\nwith illustrations in density estimation, nonparametric regression, and\nhigh-dimensional structured normal models.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 19 Apr 2016 20:10:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 25 May 2016 16:49:47 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 1 May 2017 02:17:51 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 6 Jun 2018 17:25:13 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Tue, 16 Apr 2019 15:33:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-09-25"}
